title: Optimize ARM64EC build
body:
**Description**: The ARM64EC variant of onnxruntime.dll is used to support x64 binaries running on Windows 11 + ARM64. The build has been using a mix of ARM32 intrinsic and default scalar kernels. The existing ARM64 assembly kernels cannot be used as-is because the ARM64EC sandbox: only half the NEON registers are allowed to be used at this time (x13/x14 are also off limits).

This PR adapts versions of the ARM64 kernels to the above restrictions. The qgemm kernel is roughly a port back of the NEON aarch32 kernel which also only had 16 NEON registers to work with.

The UDOT kernel will be ported in a subsequent update to further improve performance on Surface X.

title: Configuring ORTModule - Internal Options
body:
This pull request introduces a way to load configuration options in ```ORTModule``` from a json file. Configurable options include:
- Propagate cast ops
- Use external GPU allocator
- Enable custom auto grad function
- Allow layer norm mod precision
- Enable grad acc optimization
- Use static shape
- Run symbolic shape inference
- Skip check
- Debug options

To load configuration from json to ```ORTModule```, users can use the function ```load_from_json``` from inside the experimental namespace.
```py
from onnxruntime.training.ortmodule.experimental.json_config import load_from_json

# Instantiate ORTModule
model = ORTModule(pt_model)

# Load config from json
load_from_json(model, path=path_to_json)
```

Alternately, users can also set the environment variable ```ORTMODULE_JSON_CONFIG_PATH``` to the json path and avoid referencing the json path in the python script.

This pull request also includes a sample test that loads configuration from an example json file (for reference).

title: numpy_helper.to_array interpretation
body:
Hi,

I need to get the quantized values of weights and bias from a onnxrt quantized model.
These structures are stored in the graph initializer in raw_data format (TensorProto).

To decode raw_data and get values in a numpy array I use:
onnx.numpy_helper.to_array(initializer[n])

In case of weights, dtype is int8 and the array looks like:
array([[[[0x7d, 0x5a], ... f]]]], dtype=int8)
0x7d is 125 which is the right value. It works as expected.

In case of bias, dtype is int32 and the array returned by the numpy_helper.to_array function is (here, 4 bias values):
Bias= array([0xe6, 0x2a, 0x9f, 0xb3], dtype=int32)
We can see that the hexa values are not in np.int32 format.
The expected values are -8218, -5078, -2145 and -4173
I can only get them when I print explicitely Bias[0], Bias[1]...

What is wrong with the array representation in case of dtype=int32?

Why "numpy_helper.to_array" function does not return the array in clear format:
Bias=array([-8218, -5078, -2145,-4173])

Thank you,
Ocaf

title: Fix attention parity for GPT-2
body:
**Description**: 

Update attention operator to be in parity with huggingface GPT-2 & PyTorch.
(1) Use huggingface logic for unidirectional (causal) mask. Previous implementation add -10000.0, and huggingface will replace the value with -10000.0 for causal mask. This impacts the value of words masked by attention mask, and has slight impact on non masked words.
(2) Use persistent softmax in cuda to have same result as PyTorch. This seems to be major cause of fp16 difference.

After this change, CUDA result is 100% same. However CPU result still have slight difference from GEMM output.

For testing, add an environment variable (ORT_TRANSFORMER_OPTIONS=1 or 2) to enable/disable persistent softmax in attention.

Test Results:
* optimized=True, batch_size=2, hidden_size=4096, num_attention_heads=32, sequence_length=3, past_sequence_length=5, float16=False, padding_length=2, device=cuda
    * Before: Max_diff=1.7881393432617188e-07; Diff_count=100/100
    * After: Max_diff=0.0; Diff_count=0/100
* optimized=True, batch_size=2, hidden_size=4096, num_attention_heads=32, sequence_length=3, past_sequence_length=5, float16=True, padding_length=2, device=cuda
    * Before: Max_diff=0.00048828125; Diff_count=100/100
    * After: Max_diff=0.0; Diff_count=0/100
* optimized=True, batch_size=64, hidden_size=768, num_attention_heads=12, sequence_length=3, past_sequence_length=5, float16=False, padding_length=2, device=cpu
    * Before: Max_diff=1.862645149230957e-07; Diff_count=10/10
    * After: Max_diff=1.7881393432617188e-07; Diff_count=10/10

Average latency (ms) on GPT-2 (12 layers 768 hidden) with v100 GPU or CPU only:
| batch_size | sequence length | past sequence length | precision | GPU Latency (After) | GPU Latency (Before) | CPU Latency (After) | CPU Latency (Before) |
| ------- | -------  | -------  | -------  | -------  | -------  | -------  | -------  |
| 1 | 1 | 8 | FP32 | 2.57 | 2.48 | 10.35 | 10.39|
| 1 | 1 | 16 | FP32 | 2.54 | 2.52 | 10.59 | 10.09| 
| 1 | 1 | 32 | FP32 | 2.53 | 2.52 |  10.71 | 11.04|
| 1 | 1 | 64 | FP32 | 2.54 | 2.55 |  11.70 | 11.67|
| 1 | 1 | 128 | FP32 | 2.55 | 2.53 | 13.30 | 12.74|
| 1 | 1 | 8 | FP16 | 1.82 | 1.80 | NA | NA|
| 1 | 1 | 16 | FP16 | 1.81 | 1.81 | NA | NA|
| 1 | 1 | 32 | FP16 | 1.82 | 1.77 | NA | NA|
| 1 | 1 | 64 | FP16 | 1.82 | 1.82 | NA | NA|
| 1 | 1 | 128 | FP16 | 1.81 | 1.78 | NA | NA|

Using persistent softmax usually is slower (around 1%-3%). We use it by default for GPT-2, but not BERT.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

Related issues: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6549

Replaced deprecated onnxruntime-tools with newer onnxruntime in quantization transformer model notebook example

body:
**Description**: 
The newest method to quantize transformer models is described [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers). This method involves using the `optimizer` module from `onnxruntime.transformers`. However, [the notebook example for the same](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/notebooks/bert/Bert-GLUE_OnnxRuntime_quantization.ipynb) uses the deprecated `onnxruntime`. Therefore, I replaced the deprecated way of optimizing transformers to the newer, more stable version.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
This change prevents the aforementioned example notebook from not working in the near future. It also makes the examples consistent with the documentation, helping new learners of the library.

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
This change does not have a corresponding open issue.

**Additional Note:**
Another issue I found with this notebook is that it uses the `processes` module of the HuggingFace transformers library. Although the notebook works for now, this module will soon be deprecated as well. I will open a separate pull request to solve this issue so the pull requests remain organized.

title: Expand Qgemm UDOT kernel to 8x8 block
body:
Create a new M8 loop processing A[8x8] B[8x8] per iteration.
Avoid saving registers on paths that are not needed.
Adjusted M2 and M1 loop, using more registers to relax the loop carrying dependencies. 

Nearly 7% improvement observed on Surface Pro X 2 with model ssd_mobilenet_v2_300
About 4.5% improvement on resnet50 on Surface Pro X 2.

title: (WIP) [js/web] WebGL backend refactor
body:
**Description**: This PR contains several changes to the WebGL backend framework code. The major changes are:
- [x] unify concepts `ProgramInfo` and `RunData` for operator implementations. Previously it's designed based on the assumption that each operator will be implemented by using exactly 1 WebGL shader program, which is proved to be false. The old operator interface is replaced by a function-based one, using `WebGLInferenceHandler.run()` to run a program, which can be called multiple times in one operator's implementation.
- [x] remove `createProgramInfo` and `createRunData` and use one implementation function.
- [x] operator resolves to the implementation function ( instead of the instance based Operator interface)
- [x] Hide TextureLayout and TextureData from operator implementation. Now they are WebGL backend internal data structures.
- [ ] introduce `ProgramInfoLoader` for caching reusable program info. (WIP)

The behavior should not be changed before vs. after the refactoring.

Benefit of this change:
- operators are much easier to develop (ie. implement new operator, or maintain existing ones), because of the simplification on interfaces and concepts.
- artifacts cache will work as expected for all programs. (before this refactoring, the cache breaks when multiple shader programs are used in one operator implementation. )
- cleaned up blockers for some future features (eg. texture based const-folding)

title: Memory aware gradient builder.

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
Introduces a gradient graph builder feature to keep reference count (in backward pass) of activations produces in the forward pass. Using the reference count we can automatically substitute layer norm gradient operator for its corresponding invertible operator to reduce peak memory by not stashing inputs to the gradient operator from forward pass if there are no references in the backward pass. 

Using this change we see a reduction of peak memory in the forward pass by ~500MB on BERT-L, although we also see reduction in throughput/compute by 1-2% because invertible layer norm operator does slightly more computation as it takes a dependency on gamma/beta (bias) variables that also incurs memory reads.

title: [js/web] WebGL backend refactor
body:
**Description**: This PR contains several changes to the WebGL backend framework code. The major changes are:
- [x] unify concepts `ProgramInfo` and `RunData` for operator implementations. Previously it's designed based on the assumption that each operator will be implemented by using exactly 1 WebGL shader program, which is proved to be false. The old operator interface is replaced by a function-based one, using `WebGLInferenceHandler.run()` to run a program, which can be called multiple times in one operator's implementation.
- [x] remove `createProgramInfo` and `createRunData` and use one implementation function.
- [x] operator resolves to the implementation function ( instead of the instance based Operator interface)
- [x] Hide TextureLayout and TextureData from operator implementation. Now they are WebGL backend internal data structures.
- [x] introduce `ProgramInfoLoader` for caching reusable program info.

The behavior should not be changed before vs. after the refactoring.

Benefit of this change:
- operators are much easier to develop (ie. implement new operator, or maintain existing ones), because of the simplification on interfaces and concepts.
- artifacts cache will work as expected for all programs. (before this refactoring, the cache breaks when multiple shader programs are used in one operator implementation. )
- cleaned up blockers for some future features (eg. texture based const-folding)

title: Dynamic Input Reshape Incorrect
body: **Describe the bug** I have a trained Tensorflow model that has two inputs: > input0 shape: (64, 60, 257) > input1 shape: (64, 257, 60, 1) Then I converted it to ONNX model via [tf2onnx](https://github.com/onnx/tensorflow-onnx) with the command ``` # keras model !python -m tf2onnx.convert \ --saved-model ./model/myModel \ --opset 11 \ --output ./model/myModel.onnx ``` and use it for inference with dynamic input shape by the following code: ``` model = onnx.load(ONNX_PATH) # input0: 64, 60, 257 -> N, N, 257 # input1: 64, 257, 60, 1 -> N, 257, N, 1 model.graph.input[0].type.tensor_type.shape.dim[0].dim_param = '?' model.graph.input[0].type.tensor_type.shape.dim[1].dim_param = '?' model.graph.input[1].type.tensor_type.shape.dim[0].dim_param = '?' model.graph.input[1].type.tensor_type.shape.dim[2].dim_param = '?' ONNX_PATH = './model/dynamicModel.onnx' onnx.save(model, ONNX_PATH) ``` My inference code: ``` so = onnxruntime.SessionOptions() so.graph_optimization_level = onnxruntime.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_DISABLE_ALL ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(ONNX_PATH, sess_options=so) ort_session.set_providers(['CPUExecutionProvider']) # run inference preds = ort_session.run([output_name], {input_name0: x[:32], input_name1: x_norm[:32]}) ``` If I pass inputs as (64, 60, 257) and (64, 257, 60, 1), the session runs fine. But when I tried to pass inputs shaped as (32, 60, 257) and (32, 257, 60, 1), I get the following error: ``` RuntimeException: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 6 : RUNTIME_EXCEPTION : Non-zero status code returned while running Reshape node. Name:'StatefulPartitionedCall/model/1/Conv2D__36' Status Message: /onnxruntime_src/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/reshape_helper.h:42 onnxruntime::ReshapeHelper::ReshapeHelper(const onnxruntime::TensorShape&, std::vector&) gsl::narrow_cast(input_shape.Size()) == size was false. The input tensor cannot be reshaped to the requested shape. Input shape:{32,257,60,1}, requested shape:{64,1,257,60} ``` **Urgency** I'm trying to keep up with my project deadline on Aug. 13. **System information** - OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Google Colab - ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary - ONNX Runtime version: 1.6.0 - Python version: 3.7 - Visual Studio version (if applicable): - GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): - CUDA/cuDNN version: - GPU model and memory: **To Reproduce** - Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior. - Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation. - [model link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1kvUfHFJNYorUcJLVwNKcy1a8bJ1I6pZd/view?usp=sharing) **Expected behavior** The error occurs in the first operation `Reshape` as shown in this picture The reshape op is supposed to reshape input of (64, 257, 60, 1) into (64, 1, 257, 60). But the error message says `Input shape:{32,257,60,1}, requested shape:{64,1,257,60}`, which means the tensor was not reshaped correctly. **Screenshots** If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem. **Additional context** Add any other context about the problem here. If the issue is about a particular model, please share the model details as well to facilitate debugging.

title: Fix bug in CPU force fallback logic
body:
**Description**: While deciding if a node is a good candidate for forcing its execution on CPU, one of the criteria is that the node consumes all CPU inputs or "small initializers". While checking to see if an input to the node is an initializer, the search was limited just to the current scope (i.e.) if there was a good candidate for forcing onto CPU in a subgraph that was consuming an initializer from an outer scope, we would ignore such candidates just because we weren't looking in the outer scopes. This change fixes that. 

**Motivation and Context**
Found while tuning CUDA EP perf for a 1P model

title: Optimize sequence type usage on CUDA [1/n]
body:
**Description**:

Generally speaking, we tend to keep inputs/outputs of CUDA operators that are "semantically" tied to shape/shape processing on CPU (for example, indices). The advantage is two-fold:

1) While specifying that such inputs/outputs be placed on CPU in the kernel definition, it helps the force fallback logic take such hints to place related neighboring shape nodes feeding/consuming such edges on CPU. This avoids introducing a copy to device.

2) After consuming such inputs (or while producing such outputs), the CUDA kernel internally does not need to do a copy to host to bring such data to the host (write such data to the host). This avoid introducing a copy to host.  

By not doing this, it a "double whammy" - we will see 2 copies - one to take such information "semantically" tied to the host to the device for the CUDA kernel and another copy within the kernel to take it back to the host at kernel processing time. This change avoids such inefficiencies.

**Motivation and Context**
Found while tuning CUDA EP perf for a 1P model

title: Handle duplicated outputs in eval mode and under torch.no_grad context
body:
In ```eval``` mode and under ```torch.no_grad()``` context, ```ORTModule``` uses the ```inference_agent``` which uses ```IOBinding``` to execute the graph. ```IOBinding``` only registers a single output for duplicate output names. As a result, when the model has duplicated outputs, the returned values from the ORT backend will only correspond to the ones registered through ```IOBinding```.

This pull request introduces a mapping for output names to the index of the ORT outputs. And so adds support for duplicated outputs in the user model.

title: [js/web] support override wasm file path
body:
**Description**: This change adds a config into `ort.env.wasm.wasmPaths` to enable users to customize .wasm file path at runtime.

The default behavior is always looking up at the file `ort-*.wasm`(4 in total) in "current folder". Sometimes users want to put the .wasm files in different folders to the .js files.

The config `ort.env.wasm.wasmPaths` can be set to either:

- a string. In this case, it indicates the prefix on which the file name (`ort-*.wasm`) appends. Should end with a path splitter.
- an object. In this case, each of the 4 .wasm files can be customized. key is the file name and value is the override file full path.

This feature should not affect existing behavior or break existing usage.

This feature should be used in both browsers and node.js.

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
This PR includes:
- Add algorithm search for ConvGrad. Cache algorithm globally.
- Use bigger workspace size for algorithm search for both Conv and ConvGrad.
- Use Reserve() of IAllocator for allocating memory for algorithm search benchmarking, so that for Arena, we can release these memory after used instead of cached.
- Add empty_cache() for ExternalAllocator. If the memory is allocated by Reserve(), call empty_cache() when releasing the memory.

With this change, the densenet from torchvision can run 20% faster than before the change.

title: [WIP] Support custom ops ONNX schema specification using prebuilt onnxruntime
body:
**Description**: 
The purpose of this PR is to provide a way to define ONNX schema and register such schemas in to onnxruntime in python environment. The onnx::* symbols used in the custom ops shared library need to be resolved at load time from the onnx, onnx_proto libraries. The custom ops shared library (implemented as a shared library may be implemented in C/C++) may be loaded and resolved in a couple of ways:

1. Using session_options.register_custom_ops_library function (https://dev.azure.com/sajandhy/custom_ops/_git/custom_ops)
- Requires adding onnxruntime_c_api.h, onnxruntime_cxx_api.h and onnxruntime_cxx_inline.h files to the wheel
- Requires exposing onnx::* symbols through the onnxruntime_pybind11_state shared library

2. As a python module (https://dev.azure.com/sajandhy/custom_ops/_git/custom_ops_python)
- Requires exposing onnx::* symbols through the onnxruntime_pybind11_state shared library
- No header files are required to be added to wheel
*I will split this PR into two so that it is easier to review.*
I am trying to modify the PR to 
1. Only effect onnxruntime_pybind11_state.so size
2. Currently the changes only work for Ubuntu (UNIX). I will make changes to work on Windows/Apple
**Motivation and Context**

- Our 1P user wants to be able to not have to build onnxruntime in their dev workflow.

- The 1P execution provider is not built in to onnxruntime.

Thanks in advanced, Moran

title: Replace add_dependencies with target_link_libraries in library CMake
body:
It is not currently possible to build onnxruntime libraries directly from a CMake project using add_subdirectory because add_dependencies doesn't track transitive library dependencies for other targets the way target_link_libraries PUBLIC does. Replacing the add_dependencies in the various onnxruntime_<libname>.cmake files would enable a very powerful use case in the form of add_subdirectory, as everything else seems to work correctly.

ONNX Runtime version: 7b289a79
